As you emerge from the ocean in Sainte-Marie you hear the roar of airplanes above you and the murmur of French conversation all around. Although it is located off the coast of Madagascar, Réunion is one of the oversea departments of France and is therefore part of the same political, financial and social systems as the mainland. Even with less than a million inhabitants, this small island is linked by two different cable networks, giving its Internet a security and speed largely unknown to other remote locales. Accordingly, Réunion has been marketed as a gateway for Western entrepreneurs to develop business around the Indian Ocean without having to deal with the infrastructural disparities or cultural differences they might find on the African continent. From its inception as a colonial trading port to today, Réunion has been a waypoint for the movement of Western goods, information, and influence into Africa and India. From here, you might move via cable networks to the nearby island of Mauritius, or all the way across the Indian Ocean.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Đà Nẵng is a city divided by a river. Before the first bridge was built in 2000, residents had to take a ferry between the eastern shore, the site of the former French colonial settlement, and the western peninsula, which shelters the city from the sea. On the western shore lived poor fishermen, who have moved away as beach resorts populated the coast, extending south several kilometers to the site of Đà Nẵng’s international cable station. Like Vung Tau to the south, Đà Nẵng had long been connected to undersea networks, first as part of the French colonial cable system and later as part of the Americans' wartime communications strategy. Đà Nẵng’s international cable station, however, was the first built with the support of the national telecommunications carrier, Vietnam Posts and Telecommunications. While the city's infrastructures, from bridges to cable systems, bring connections, they also bring the expansion of capitalism, providing benefits to some at the expense of others.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: “What happens when a friendly beach town opens its port for global communication?” the Grover Beach city website boasts, “You get the perfect place to surf both the waves and the web!” The cable landing here is one of three international gateways nestled in the rolling hills of San Luis Obispo. Like the stations to which it connects, at Harbour Pointe, Washington and Ajigaura, Japan, however, Grover Beach's station was a new node in the undersea network, constructed specifically for the PC-1 Network. The station also remains the west coast’s only undersea gateway to Central America, as it connects to Panama, Mexico, and Costa Rica via the Pan American Crossing. As such, the city pitches itself as the shortest path, with the least travel time, to Japan and South America. Seeking to leverage their position in the cable network, Grover Beach politicians developed a “Technology Master Plan,” applied for Federal stimulus monies, and have branded themselves as the “virtual port” in order to build out the region’s broadband and technology industries.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Arriving in Bangladesh you are greeted by the gentle sandy slope of Kolatoli beach, a lengthy expanse that accommodates both the safe passage of cables below and the leisure of tourists above. This is the only undersea cable landing in this country, whose Internet speeds and penetration rate are among the lowest in the world, though there are those who seek to change this. In 2008 the Bangladesh Awami League party successfully campaigned on a vision of a “Digital Bangladesh,” imagining a country transformed in 2021, both economically and politically, by the open, connective promise of the web. Years later, however, progress remains elusive. Internet surveillance and censorship remain an ongoing issue for Bangladesh’s small community of Internet users, while the national government has experienced several security leaks in the process of digitizing its operations. It nevertheless remains committed to the Digital Bangladesh vision, and has agreed to fund a second submarine cable link with a $40 million loan from the Islamic Development Bank. The remaining funds to support the project will be generated by selling bandwidth from the Cox’s Bazar cable, most of which is presently unused.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Your path from Hawai‘i via American Samoa brings you to a cable station housed within the curved, glass and metal headquarters of SamoaTel, the country’s primary telecom provider. Built in 2004 and connected to the underwater network five years later, the facility is located about a quarter mile inland from Apia’s exposed harbor, making it less vulnerable to tropical cyclones. One of the earliest recorded storms occurred in 1889 when colonial powers were vying for control of the islands. Engaged in a tense standoff in the port, German, British, and U.S. ships were destroyed by massive waves after they refused to evacuate. Several additional cyclones hit the low-lying city in the 1990s and early 2000s, causing severe flooding and damage to infrastructure. Gale-force winds also disrupted satellite communications, motivating investment in a more resilient submarine link.
